I have a small sweet little white Pomeranian and he has had allergies and immune issues all his life.  He was in swim therapy after he had knee surgery to help him recover and get stronger but being exposed to water, no matter how clean his home is and his bedding and how natural his food is, he still would get an ear infection or coat yeast infection.  He seemed to pick up the coat issues after walking in areas where the plants were dead and some of the area on the walk path was damp.  He came down with an ear infection from swim therapy but we have been trying to avoid the constant use of antibiotics because of his system and he is an older dog.

I bought this hoping it would help clear up my dog's ear infection.  It did not.  I  used the Zymox Ear Cleanser for a week and it did not do anything.

I eventually found after searching the internet, an all natural solution!  This natural remedy was a great help and has nearly wiped out the problem altogether.  Old fashion vinegar and water!

I made of 1 part vinegar and 2 parts water and used that instead of the bottled product.  I would use the water and vinegar with a cotton ball and gently swab out the brown yeasty paste that was in my dog's ear.  This natural remedy did much better than the Zymox ear cleanser.  After one use, my dog's ears showed sign of improvement using the vinegar and water.

My friend told me to try the Zymox with the hydrocordizone.  So I bought the Zymox with hydrocordizone 0.5%.  This formula is a thick enzymatic gel and it helped break up the dog's ear yeast infection, especially deep down inside the ear.  But he still itched and wobbled his head a lot because the solution would get stuck down in his ear and not come out.  Poor thing.

I started using the vinegar and water solution again and the gunk began to make its way out of his ears. I would swab them out with a cotton ball using vinegar and water and it immediately did a better job than using the Zymox with hydrocordizone by itself.  So I would alternate, using the gel one day and the vinegar and water the next, allowing the dead material time to come out.  After a few days, his ears looked really clean and he does not show any signs of wobbling, discomfort, or itching.  His ears are pink and clean now, not red and itchy.

 I think you are better off using a solution of vinegar and water which I have found, incidently, to be great for coat problems and bacteria or fungal infections.  Just give the dog a bath really good and use a ratio of one part vinegar to 3 parts water, or four parts water depending on the sensitivity of your dog, and let it soak in, and then rinse and condition your dog as usual.  Between baths, I use the vinegar/water solution with cotton balls to swab the infected areas of the coat (if I see a break out) and it clears it up.  It will take a good month of close attention to get rid of yeast, fungal, and bacteria infections on a dog and you have to wash the bedding frequently to make any solid progress.

I would not use this Zymox Ear Cleanser again because it did not seem to do anything at all but I would recommend the Zymox hydrocortizone 0.5% enzyme gel.  I think they make a stronger solution as well.

Mostly, the vinegar and water I think makes a great combination to really cleanse and kill the infection at its source.  (Don't poke around in your dog's ear with Q tips unless you know what you are doing and how to gently do it around the edges and not the inside.  Better to use clean fresh cotton balls and don't use cotton balls that have been swabbed in one ear. Don't use the cotton balls on one ear and then on the other or you will risk spreading infection to the other ear!)  If you use vinegar and water for the ears, use separate cotton balls to swab and make sure the cotton balls are at least half saturated and then gently squeezed out before you apply it to the ears.

Caution:  Don't make the vinegar too strong or you'll risk burning your dog's ears and tender ear drums!
summary: THIS DID NOT WORK BUT OTHER ZYMOX SOLUTIONS AND VINEGAR AND WATER DID!

My puppies love this food! We read an article about best dog foods and this was on it. Our breeder used Hill Science Diet with the same flavor as this and so we continued that for the first few weeks until I read that article and found that Hills Science was one on the list that they DON'T recommend. The list contained a lot of very expensive foods and this one was one of the cheapest on the list so we thought we'd try.

Differences: 1. The food pellets are smaller and more rounded. 2. When you add water (because they are puppies), it turns to a gravy. Hills food just expanded like a sponge but did not turn into a gravy. 3. My puppies LOVE it! They practically inhale the food. With Hills, they would just eat the food but it took a while and some times they would not even finish it. With this food, they are excited to eat and they finish every bit and want more. They want to eat all day long now! They are constantly checking the kitchen to see if we've put more food down for them.

We have two Vizsla puppies from the same litter. One has slightly looser stools and gas (after switching to this) and the other does not. I think that means that, the "loose stool" and "gas" issues are going to be on an individual dog basis. We have only used the dog food for 4 days.

The difference in appearance was enough to convince me and I am willing to put up with the issues as long as it doesn't cause them pain or harm. That has not been the case yet. I will give it another 3 weeks before making the final decision on whether one needs to be changed to another food. I would hate to do that though, because she loves this food

If unsupervised he might, but you'd be able to tell as this toy is quite loud and you'd know it had stopped.

This ball is a great distraction for him so he isn't always bothering us when we are trying to get something done.  A really good way to put that puppy energy to use.

With how destructive he is, if it holds up for even a month, it will fully deserve these 5 stars.

EDIT: Several weeks and many uses later and it's still holding up well.  Some tooth marks but no actual damage despite some gnawing.

He has yet to pop it open even once.  To all the people who have had that happen, tighten the threads more.

reviewText: My cats are still getting used to it and are not very happy with me. One of my cats would constantly throw up after eating and every other cause was ruled out. In regards to design, the white base around it needs to be larger. When they pull out a food piece onto the white part, they have a hard time eating it, as the tunnel edges get in the way. They then have to knock it on the ground to actually eat it. If the white base extended out further, this would not be a problem. Actually, now that I think about it, It would be better if it wasn't a circle either. They seem to eat one side and then I have to turn it around when those tunnels are empty. If the tunnels were in a line and it had a wider base, it would be much better!

reviewText: Worked well for my 17 pound pug!

We have two of these, in use for two years by our German shepherd mix. Both beds are still in great shape and I'm considering a third, because she loves to lie in various places and I think the foam is healthier on a big dog's joints. The foam has held up well, still fluffy and soft - it doesn't seem to have compressed or hardened over the years.

The cover is surprisingly nice, soft fleece - I would not mind a jacket lined with this stuff. It zips off easily for washing.  I've only washed the fleece cover a couple times because I put the entire bed, including fleece cover, inside another cover. (If you want a more stylish cover, the Molly Mutt brand makes covers that nicely fit both the medium and large beds.) One nice feature is that inside the fleece cover, the foam itself is covered in another layer of white fabric. This both protects the foam from invading dog hair and debris, and makes it easier to slip off the fleece cover.

These may seem a little pricey, but if your pup's not a bed destroyer these are absolutely worth it. I recently had to toss out another foam bed of about the same age, and I wish I'd just invested in another one of these instead of that cheaper one.
summary: Still happy after two years of use

My best guess is that even well after the item was delivered, it showed as 'in transit' - in fact, I got a 'shipment delayed' notification *after* it had arrived, and I couldn't do the return for two days until it finally showed as 'delivered' - so maybe that also has something to do with it not showing as a verified purchase.) This was really disappointing, as the description says that you can adjust the chest strap, but actually it's the belly strap that is adjustable. And it was especially disappointing as the harness seems *really* comfy and well-made! BUT..here's what I learned... I was curious that the brand label on the sides (in this case Golden Panda) is simply affixed with velco. In researching more, it turns out that this harness is being sold by lots of different companies, and they just swap in their brand label. So, this harness is being sold in *all* sizes (XS through XL) by Unho, here UNHO Dog Body Harness Padded for Dogs from All kinds of size I just ordered a S from Unho, and will be sure to review it there!

Well - I guess I'll be breaking the trend of 5-star reviews. Here's why:

Pros:
- It does a good job of removing most fur.
- The slider for fur removal is a good concept (though it's been used to greater effect in other products)

Cons:
- Shallow teeth. While this brush does a good job removing fur, the shallow teeth mean the brush needs to constantly be pruned of fur every 2-3 strokes. Even then, my floor and my person are covered with fur within minutes (my pup gets brushed 1-2 times per week)
- My pup is medium sized (50 lbs) with a double coat. The teeth are too shallow to reach some parts of her undercoat.
- The brush itself is a bit flimsy, and small. The junction between the head and handle is loose, and I've had it less than a month.

Great alternative to the expensive name-brand version. Works really well on 2 fat, incredibly-sheddy orange tabbies. I don't really use the button/lever to get the hair off, but appreciate the option. I get so much off of the cats that it's easier and more satisfying to pull it off by hand.

"kanamycin and amikacin are very effective against Gram-negative bacteria when given by injection. However, they cause kidney damage in fish when given by this route.  Kanamycin and neomycin may be effective against external infections if used in bath treatments. So going by the above research from Dr. Govind Pandey... Kanamycin can cause kidney damage and is good for gastrointestinal bacterial infections BUT if the fish already has kidney problems with dropsy FORGET IT! its only going to come back and end up killing the fish with kidney failure. So now what? No wonder everyone says it works but then Dropsy comes back again later and kills the fish. Now I know why the experts say its better to euthanize the fish with clove oil because there really is no cure for Dropsy symptoms YET but is there?  How about what they use to treat humans with bacterial, pathogens and kidney problems? or dogs and cats? Lets research that and go from there. Probiotics, enzymes and anti-parasite Herbs are a big break through for treating bacterial and pathogen parasitic Infections how about some of these may work for fish too?

Kanamycin
"This medicine may cause kidney problems, nerve problems, and hearing problems (like long-lasting hearing loss). This could even happen at normal doses. The risk of these problems may be higher if you already have kidney or hearing problems, if you get high doses of kanamycin, or if you get kanamycin for a long time. For starters, my wife should probably have written this review, since she buys the litter, and (for the most part) scoops/changes the box. However, because I'm not a big cat person, I think I can offer a critically fair review.
The idea of cat poo/pee indoors doesn't sit well with me, so I'm always up for my wife trying something new, which will better absorb odor, and not make a huge mess. We used Tidy Cat for the longest, and it's ok, as far as basic litters go. When our cat was injured, we moved to the recycled newspaper litter, so it wouldn't stick to her fur while she healed; it wasn't bad, but not the greatest to scoop (the plus side was that there was virtually no mess from our cat exiting the box). We then tried Feline Pine (I believe is the name), and that was a disaster. It smelled like pine out of the bag, but began to smell almost immediately. My wife then decided to branch out and try Nature's Miracle JFC Corn Cob cat litter.
Now, here is a break down of Pros and Cons:
Pros:
-It has a light, organic smell, pretty much like what you would expect from ground up corn cob; it's not strong and has no perfumes.
-It clumps fairly well.
-It absorbs odor equal to any clay or other organic litter we've tried--not better, not worse.
-There's no dust/residual that would be harmul to breathe.

Cons:
-It can be kind of messy. Because it is ground up cob, the individual grains are very light and can easily go everywhere if disturbed, so be prepared to sweep up often.
-While it does absorb odor, when the box needs to be changed, it can be quite odorous. Again, it's corn cob, which, when combined with wet waste, gives off an odor that resembles rotting produce. Seriously. Right after we started using it, I went into our utility room, and noticed what smelled like produce that had sat in the garbage too long. I couldn't figure out where the smell was coming from, because the utility room is upstairs, and the odor didn't initially resemble a litter box in need of changing. I looked all over the room, trying to figure out how old veggies would've ended up in there (we do have kids, after all), and happened to be on my hands and knees looking around near the cat box, when it dawned on me what I was actually smelling: urine-saturated corn cob.

All in all, I can't complain too much about this product, because it doesn't cling to our cat's fur or paws, it has no dust or strong odors, and performs pretty well. Having had a cat in the house for a decade, and having tried tons of different litters, I can say that there is no miracle litter out there. However, this does the trick decently, and again that's coming from someone who doesn't like the concept of litter boxes to begin with.
Hope this helps!
summary: Decent Corn Cob Cat Litter, Yes. Miracle? No.

I got these after a lot of good reviews in attempt not to have to declaw my cats. Both of my cats were born on farms and have strong natural instincts. Every time I applied these my cats would cry, struggle, hiss, and bite (things they don't do when I just trim their nails). Then they would spend the next two weeks trying to physically pry them off, sometimes to the point of wounding themselves and bleeding all over. I would find the fake nails with clumps of fur, or parts of their actual claws in my carpeting.

For those of you who are morally opposed to having cats declawed, perhaps try this first. However, after a destroyed couch I got my cats front claws removed, they were running around like normal and happy again 2 days later. They use their litter box and have the same behaviors before the operation. For my cats, I think they were absolutely off getting declawed. They showed signs of severe stress, were moody towards me and each other, and physically harmed themselves trying to remove these.
summary: Cats injured themselves trying to get off. HORRIBLE SOLUTION TO DECLAWING for more instinctual cats.

reviewText:
I have bought a lot of cat toys over the years but this is the one they absolutely go bonkers for.  It was a last second purchase.  I had already grabbed 3 cat toys I was going to try when I saw this one.  It was $14.00 where I bought it (which was a little more than I wanted to pay) but I purchased it anyway.  I have a few kitties in dire need of a little weight loss.  From the moment I took it out of the package my cats loved it.  I have 6 living in the house and every single one of them love to bat it, chase it, bite it, and sometimes run off with it. When they hear me pressing the button to activate the dragonfly they come running.  I will say that the cord is a little flimsy so if your cats like to chew cords you may want to buy a second one or maybe use a little electrical tape?  I haven't had any other issues with this toy.  I think I have used it so much that the battery may be about to run down, but I think I will just buy a new one.  If you have been searching for a cat toy that your cats won't turn their noses up at, I believe this one is it.  2 paws up!

If you find my review useful please let me know and if you have any questions or comments, feel free to post them below and I will answer them as quickly as possible. Thank you for checking out my review. :)
